---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Rugby 101 — Spotsylvania RFC"
  description="New to rugby? Everything a parent or beginner needs to know — what rugby is, safety, youth formats, and what to expect at a first practice."
  ogTitle="Rugby 101 — Spotsylvania RFC"
  ogDescription="What is rugby? Is it safe? What happens at the first practice? Answers for parents and beginners considering Spotsylvania RFC."
>
  <Header />

  <main id="main-content">

    <div class="ph-outer">
      <div class="ph-inner">
        <p class="section-label">New to Rugby</p>
        <h1 class="section-title">Rugby 101.</h1>
        <p class="section-body">
          If you have never watched a rugby match or coached a rugby session, that is fine. Most of
          the people who will build this club are in the same position. Here is what you need to
          know.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="section">
      <p class="section-label">The Basics</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What is <em>rugby?</em></h2>
      <p class="section-body">
        Rugby is a field sport played with an oval ball. Players can run with the ball, pass it
        laterally or backward, and kick it forward. The objective is to score tries — grounding the
        ball over the opponent's try line — or to kick goals through upright posts.
      </p>
      <div class="fact-grid">
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-label">Team Size</div>
          <p>15 players per side in full rugby union. Smaller formats — sevens, tens, tag — use
          fewer players and are common starting points for beginners and youth.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-label">The Ball</div>
          <p>An oval ball, slightly larger than an American football. Passing is lateral or
          backward — you cannot throw the ball forward to a teammate.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-label">Continuous Play</div>
          <p>Rugby has very few stoppages compared to American sports. The game flows. Players
          develop fitness, spatial awareness, and decision-making under pressure.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="fact-card">
          <div class="fact-label">Every Shape. Every Size.</div>
          <p>Rugby has a position for every body type. Speed, strength, endurance, size — the
          game needs all of it. Forwards and backs require different skills and builds.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section-alt">
      <p class="section-label">Why Rugby</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Why youth <em>rugby?</em></h2>
      <p class="section-body">
        Rugby develops qualities that transfer far beyond the pitch. The structure of the game
        demands things of young players that most other sports do not.
      </p>
      <dl class="why-list">
        <div class="why-item">
          <dt>Decision-making under pressure</dt>
          <dd>
            Rugby asks players to read play, communicate, and make fast decisions with real
            consequences. There is no play-calling from the sideline on every possession.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div class="why-item">
          <dt>Genuine teamwork</dt>
          <dd>
            Individual talent matters less in rugby than in most sports. Every position is
            essential. A team that works together beats a team of individuals almost every time.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div class="why-item">
          <dt>Respect as a rule</dt>
          <dd>
            Respect for referees, opponents, and teammates is a core part of rugby's culture — not
            a stated value, but an enforced expectation. Players are held to it consistently.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div class="why-item">
          <dt>Fellowship that lasts</dt>
          <dd>
            Rugby players tend to stay connected to their club long after they stop playing. The
            friendships formed through shared effort and honest competition run deep.
          </dd>
        </div>
        <div class="why-item">
          <dt>Physical development</dt>
          <dd>
            Rugby builds fitness, coordination, strength, and spatial awareness. The physical
            demands are broad — not specialised around one movement pattern.
          </dd>
        </div>
      </dl>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <p class="section-label">Safety</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">Is it <em>safe?</em></h2>
      <p class="section-body">
        Safety is the right question to ask. Here is an honest answer.
      </p>
      <div class="two-col">
        <div>
          <h3 class="sub-heading">The first phase is non-contact</h3>
          <p>
            The youth programme will begin with tag rugby — a non-contact format where defenders
            remove a tag from the ball-carrier's belt instead of tackling. There are no scrums,
            rucks, mauls, or contact drills in tag rugby. It is the same starting point used by
            USA Rugby's youth development pathway.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="sub-heading">Contact is introduced progressively</h3>
          <p>
            When and if the programme advances to contact rugby, tackling technique is taught
            methodically — starting from stationary positions, progressing to controlled movement,
            and only then applied in game situations. Proper technique is the primary injury
            prevention tool.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="sub-heading">Coaches will be trained</h3>
          <p>
            USA Rugby requires coach certification for registered play. Our coaches will complete
            relevant training before working with players. Certified coaching means consistent
            technique, appropriate progressions, and a shared standard of care.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="sub-heading">Context matters</h3>
          <p>
            Contact sports carry risk. Rugby is honest about that. The question is whether the
            risk is managed well and proportionate to the benefit. We believe it is — and we
            intend to manage it properly, not minimise it rhetorically.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section section-alt">
      <p class="section-label">First Practice</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">What to <em>expect.</em></h2>
      <p class="section-body">
        If your child has never played rugby, here is what a first session at Spotsylvania RFC
        will look like.
      </p>
      <ol class="expect-list">
        <li class="expect-item">
          <div class="expect-num" aria-hidden="true">1</div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="sub-heading">Warm-up and movement</h3>
            <p>
              A structured warm-up — running, agility, basic movement patterns. Nothing technically
              demanding. The goal is to get bodies moving and players comfortable on the field.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="expect-item">
          <div class="expect-num" aria-hidden="true">2</div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="sub-heading">Handling and passing</h3>
            <p>
              Basic ball handling — holding the ball correctly, passing laterally, catching under
              light pressure. These fundamentals take time to develop and are worth doing slowly.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="expect-item">
          <div class="expect-num" aria-hidden="true">3</div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="sub-heading">Rules introduction</h3>
            <p>
              A brief, practical introduction to the laws that matter most for beginners — forward
              pass, tag rules, scoring, basic field orientation. Enough to play a game.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="expect-item">
          <div class="expect-num" aria-hidden="true">4</div>
          <div>
            <h3 class="sub-heading">A short game</h3>
            <p>
              Players apply what they have learned in a small-sided game. Mistakes are expected and
              used as teaching moments. The aim is for everyone to touch the ball often.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <p class="section-label">Getting Started</p>
      <h2 class="section-title">No experience <em>required.</em></h2>
      <p class="section-body">
        The programme is being built for beginners. If your child has never played, they are not
        behind — they are exactly who this is for. The same is true for coaches, volunteers, and
        supporters. We are all learning this together.
      </p>
      <a href="/#interest" class="btn-primary">Join the Founding List</a>
    </section>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .ph-outer {
    background: var(--green);
    padding: 0 24px;
  }

  .ph-inner {
    max-width: 1100px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: calc(var(--section-pad-v) + 52px) 0 var(--section-pad-v);
  }

  .ph-outer .section-label { color: var(--gold); }
  .ph-outer .section-title { color: var(--cream); }
  .ph-outer .section-title em { color: var(--gold); }
  .ph-outer .section-body { color: rgba(246, 242, 230, 0.75); margin-bottom: 0; }

  .section-alt {
    background: var(--light);
  }

  .fact-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(240px, 1fr));
    gap: 32px;
    margin-top: 48px;
  }

  .fact-card {
    border-top: 3px solid var(--gold);
    padding-top: 20px;
  }

  .fact-label {
    font-family: 'Oswald', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.14em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--navy);
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }

  .fact-card p {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .why-list {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .why-item {
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(30, 61, 46, 0.12);
    padding: 28px 0;
  }

  .why-item:last-child {
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(30, 61, 46, 0.12);
  }

  dt {
    font-family: 'Oswald', sans-serif;
    font-size: 1rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--navy);
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }

  dd {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.97rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--muted);
  }

  .two-col {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(280px, 1fr));
    gap: 40px 60px;
    margin-top: 48px;
  }

  .sub-heading {
    font-family: 'Oswald', sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--navy);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
  }

  .two-col p {
    font-size: 0.97rem;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .expect-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 48px 0 0;
  }

  .expect-item {
    display: flex;
    gap: 36px;
    padding: 32px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(30, 61, 46, 0.12);
  }

  .expect-item:last-child {
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(30, 61, 46, 0.12);
  }

  .expect-num {
    font-family: 'Playfair Display', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 2.4rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--gold);
    opacity: 0.55;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    line-height: 1;
    padding-top: 4px;
    min-width: 40px;
  }

  .expect-item p {
    font-size: 0.97rem;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
